							</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-22T16:06:24+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 22, 2014 12:06 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 22, 2014 12:06 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/22/the-diminishing-american-edge/" data-title="The Diminishing American Edge" data-description="The slipping economic advantages of the American middle class.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last week, in a tax day post defending <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/15/the-case-against-higher-taxes/?module=BlogPost-Title&amp;version=Blog%20Main&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Body">the virtues of light taxation</a>, I discussed the various economic advantages that the United States of America has reaped from its lower-than-average tax burden, and the evidence that not only the U.S. but also our developed-world peers have benefited from the American style of free market capitalism. But I concluded by allowing that this argument would look that much weaker the longer the U.S. economy goes without delivering on the second half of the basic American &#8220;more risk and more inequality for more growth and jobs and self-sufficiency&#8221; bargain â a combinationÂ which has held historically, but not so much of late.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you&#8217;re looking for a detailed illustration of that point, look no further than <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/upshot/the-american-middle-class-is-no-longer-the-worlds-richest.html?rref=upshot&amp;_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=The%20Upshot&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article">the lead feature on The Upshot</a>, the new data-journalism hub just launched by my colleague David Leonhardt, which shows the American middle class losing its longstanding disposable-income advantage over some of the richer social democracies. Here&#8217;s a key paragraph:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Median per capita income was $18,700 in the United States in 2010 (which translates to about $75,000 for a family of four after taxes), up 20 percent since 1980 but virtually unchanged since 2000, after adjusting for inflation. The same measure, by comparison, rose about 20 percent in Britain between 2000 and 2010 and 14 percent in the Netherlands. Median income also rose 20 percent in Canada between 2000 and 2010, to the equivalent of $18,700.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#8217;d also recommend <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/upshot/this-simple-table-summarizes-our-story-on-american-living-standards.html?smid=tw-upshotnyt&amp;_r=0">this table</a>Â from the story, which shows how American income at each decile compares to disposable income in other developed economies. <span id="more-19733"></span>You&#8217;ll see that nations like Canada, Norway, and Denmark began to outperform the U.S. in the 1980s when it came to (post-tax, post-transfer) incomes well below the median, but that the American middle class&#8217;s historic edge seemed to stabilize across the 1990sÂ â only to slip and slip across the 2000s, as the Canadians and Norwegians and Dutch passed us for incomes in the 30th and 40th percentile, and then Canada equalled (and passed, perhaps, if other estimates for the last few years are right) our median as well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now, some major caveats are in order here. There&#8217;s <a href="//www.cbc.ca/news/business/fears-of-a-housing-bubble-in-canada-overblown-report-says-1.2581913">a vigorous debate</a> north of the border over how bubble-y Canada&#8217;s housing market really is, but those of who remember similar debates in the mid-2000s in the United States haveÂ <a href="//business.time.com/2014/01/17/canada-has-its-own-housing-bubble-and-its-about-to-burst/">reason to be skeptical</a> that Canada&#8217;s recent run-up in middle class income will be sustainable in the long run. (My old friend Reihan Salam argues that the housing issue <a href="//www.nationalreview.com/agenda/376293/house-prices-are-important-simple-explanation-why-us-middle-class-has-fared-poorly">has broader global applications</a>Â for median income as well.) Some of the other nations that have passed us are not exactly ideal comparative models: Norway is basically a petro-state, and thus a long-running outlier in per capita G.D.P. statistics; the Netherlands is a micro-economy and micro-society compared to the United States; etc. If you take <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/upshot/the-american-middle-class-is-no-longer-the-worlds-richest.html?rref=upshot&amp;_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=The%20Upshot&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article">the first graphic in the story</a> and compare America&#8217;s recent performance to the three largest European economiesÂ â France, Germany and the United Kingdom Â â our trajectory looks a lot better: We&#8217;ve lost median-income ground relative to the U.K. (which, N.B., has the lowest tax burden of the three) over the last decade-and-a-half, but we&#8217;ve actually gained ground relative to the Germans (whose wage stagnation is discussed <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/upshot/how-underpaid-german-workers-helped-cause-europes-debt-crisis.html?rref=upshot">elsewhere on the Upshot</a>) and the French.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But with that said,Â <em>hey, we&#8217;re outperforming the French</em><em>Â </em>is not the most powerful rebuttal to the point that the U.S. economy is not delivering the kind of broadly-shared prosperity that most Americans have historically associated with the promise of our model. And I think the decile table cited above is a good way to think about the politics surrounding these issues going forward. If we get back to where we were in the 1990s, with an economy that&#8217;s delivering for the 40th-through-the-60th percentiles but a welfare state that isn&#8217;t as generous as the social democracies to the 10th-through-30th, most Americans will probably be inclined to say, well, that&#8217;s just our system&#8217;s traditional &#8220;growth over fairness, opportunity over equality&#8221; trade-off working as expected, and there will be more support for efforts to keep the tax-and-transfer share of the U.S. economy close to historic norms. (Though it would help, obviously, if there were more mobility <em>out of</em> the 10th and 20th percentiles than we&#8217;re currently seeing.) But if the advantages of the American system are only visible from, say, the 70th or even 80th percentile up, then the case for the low-tax model will seem weaker relative to how its been received and debated in the past, and American politics will probably shift leftward on size-of-government issues (as it already has among the rising generation).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In either scenario, though, I still think that (as I argued in <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/opinion/sunday/douthat-marx-rises-again.html?ref=rossdouthat">my Sunday column</a> on <em>le grand dÃ©bat de Piketty</em>) there will be a lot more stability in our politics and our society than some of the &#8220;new gilded age&#8221; arguments imply. But I&#8217;ll elaborate on that point in a later post.</p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
